# Interactive HTML — Cursor adapter

Drop this rule into any project's `.cursor/rules/` and ask Cursor:

> "make this page interactive"
>
> "process new comments"
>
> "stop the interactive server"

You become the agent for the Interactive HTML loop: the user comments in the
page; you read the comments, edit the HTML, and append a response.

## Setup flow

When the user asks to make a page interactive:

1. Identify the target directory — default to the current workspace root.
   If the user names a folder, use that. If it has no `*.html`, offer to
   create one from their content.

2. Start the server only (no separate agent — you are the agent). Run this
   in a background terminal:

   ```bash
   python <IH_HOME>/cli/ih.py <dir> --no-watch --no-open
   ```

   Replace `<IH_HOME>` with the path where you installed
   `github.com/machbuilds/interactive-html`. The launcher auto-bumps off a
   busy port; capture the URL it prints.

3. Tell the user the page URL(s).

4. **Wait for the user to submit a comment.** The browser writes to
   `<dir>/.ih/comments.jsonl`. When the user says "process new comments"
   (or you observe a new batch), go to **Responding to a batch**.

> Note: Cursor doesn't have a "Monitor file" tool the way Claude Code does,
> so you can't sit idle watching the inbox. The pattern is: user submits,
> then asks you to process — one short turn per round.

## Responding to a batch

When the user asks you to process new comments (or when you read
`<dir>/.ih/comments.jsonl` and find an unhandled `batch_id`):

1. Read the latest unprocessed line(s) in `<dir>/.ih/comments.jsonl`. Each
   comment has a stable `id`, a `kind` (`text` / `element` / `general`),
   and an `anchor` with a CSS `selector`, `tag`, `quote`, and
   `html_snippet`. **Locate elements by visible text or `html_snippet`**,
   not by selector alone.

2. Read `<dir>/.ih/updates.json` to see what's already been handled — the
   union of `changes[*].in_response_to` is the set of resolved comment ids.

3. Edit the relevant `*.html` file(s) to address each new comment. Keep
   edits minimal and focused on what was asked.

4. Wrap each logical change in `<span data-ih-change="ch-<slug>">…</span>`,
   or add `data-ih-change="ch-<slug>"` to an existing wrapping element.
   Exactly one anchor per change.

5. **Append** one batch object to `<dir>/.ih/updates.json` (it's a JSON
   array — read, push, write back). Schema:

   ```json
   {
     "batch_id": "u-<short-slug>",
     "timestamp": "<ISO 8601 UTC>",
     "in_response_to_batch": "<batch_id from the inbox>",
     "changes": [
       {
         "id": "ch-<slug>",
         "anchor": "ch-<slug>",
         "in_response_to": ["<comment id>"],
         "title": "short, concrete label",
         "description": "one or two sentences for the record"
       }
     ]
   }
   ```

The server detects the update and pushes an SSE event; the page reloads
(scroll preserved) and walks the user through the changes via the
`data-ih-change` anchors.

## Rules

- Edit only `*.html` files and `.ih/updates.json`.
- Every `id` in updates.json must have a matching `data-ih-change` in the
  HTML, and every new `data-ih-change` must appear in updates.json.
- `comments.jsonl` is append-only — never modify existing lines.

## Stop flow

```bash
lsof -ti:<port> | xargs kill
```

The server also self-retires on parent-death and after the configured idle
timeout, so simply closing the terminal cleans it up.

## Removal flow

Strip the client tags for a clean static copy:

```bash
python <IH_HOME>/cli/inject.py <dir> --remove
```

## Protocol reference

The file formats and HTTP surface are documented at
`PROTOCOL.md` in the Interactive HTML repo. Anything not covered here is
covered there.
